I";<p>For speakers of <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/unsupervised-learning-derives-semantics-from-non-human-languages">languages</a> which use alphabets, internalizing the <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/multi-modal-representations-foster-understanding">multi-modal</a> representations of <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/logograms-resemble-vector-quantization">logograms</a> is difficult. Each one has visual, phonetic, and semantic features which have to be <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/optimizing-for-short-semantic-distances-fosters-learning">linked</a>. Romanization provides a <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/concept-learning-is-few-shot-scaffolding-supported-by-working-memory">scaffold</a> based on phonetic features, anchoring the visuals and semantics.</p>
